### Mechanic 1: Audio / Music Output System  
**Owner: Jake**

The audio mechanic will use one WAV file and multiple MIDI files to create musical outputs that the rest of the project can use. The WAV file will act as the main sound that the audience hears, while the MIDI files will provide structured data for the code. This means the project can know when a kick, snare, hi-hat, piano note, guitar note, or bass note is happening without relying only on FFT guessing. The MIDI data can create both monophonic triggers, such as one drum hit, and polyphonic triggers, such as multiple notes playing at the same time.

This mechanic also connects to the idea that the artwork can shape the music. Some visual elements may mute, unmute, switch, or change the volume of different musical parts. There will also be an FFT aspect where the final sound output can be analysed, so frequency content can influence visual movement, colour, or atmosphere. This mechanic is important because it becomes the “music brain” of the project, giving the other mechanics simple musical outputs to respond to.

Example outputs may include:

`bassKick`, `snareDrum`, `closedHihat`, `pianoNote`, `guitarNote`, `bassNote`, `bassVolume`, `drumVolume`, and `fftEnergy`.

![Audio mechanic diagram](images/audio-midi-diagram.png)

---

### Mechanic 2: Random Animation  
**Owner: Team Member 2**

The random animation mechanic will create moving visual elements that feel alive and unpredictable. This mechanic will use random values to control properties such as position, size, speed, colour, direction, and shape behaviour. For example, small particles, circles, or lines may appear in different parts of the canvas and move in slightly different ways each time. Some of these objects may respond to musical outputs, such as becoming larger when the kick drum is triggered or changing direction when a snare hit occurs.

This mechanic connects to our project vision because we want the artwork to feel like a living system rather than a fixed animation. Randomness will make the piece feel less mechanical and more organic. However, the randomness will still be connected to the audio system, so it does not feel completely disconnected from the music. The user may not directly control every random element, but they will experience the artwork as constantly changing and responsive. This mechanic will help create energy, surprise, and movement across the canvas.

Possible code ideas may include random positions, random colours, random object sizes, and random movement directions.

![Random animation sketch](images/random-animation-sketch.png)

---

### Mechanic 3: Background Visual  
**Owner: Team Member 3**

The background visual mechanic will create the atmosphere of the piece. Instead of keeping the background as a flat colour, this mechanic will use movement, gradients, waves, particles, or Perlin noise to make the background feel connected to the music. For example, low-frequency energy from the FFT could make the background pulse slowly, while higher frequencies could create sharper flickers, small particles, or brighter textures. The background may also change depending on which musical layer is active, such as drums, bass, piano, or guitar.

This mechanic connects to our project vision because the background will hold all the other mechanics together visually. While the music output system provides triggers and the random animation creates movement, the background visual will create the overall mood. It can make the piece feel calm, intense, chaotic, or atmospheric depending on the music. This mechanic may use Perlin noise to create smoother motion, so the background feels natural rather than completely random. It will help unify the whole canvas and make the project feel like one coherent audiovisual world.

Possible visual ideas include noise-based clouds, pulsing gradients, moving waves, and frequency-reactive colour shifts.

![Background visual reference](images/background-visual-sketch.png)

---

### Mechanic 4: Visual Control of Audio Effects  
**Owner: Team Member 4**

The visual control mechanic will allow parts of the artwork to affect the audio. Instead of the sound only controlling the visuals, this mechanic explores the opposite direction: visual movement can control sound behaviour. For example, the position, size, or movement of a shape could control the volume of an audio layer. A shape moving across the canvas could slowly increase or decrease the volume of the bass, piano, or drums. Another visual object could act like a switch, turning a sound layer on or off when it enters a certain area.

This mechanic connects strongly to the project vision because it creates a feedback relationship between image and sound. The artwork is not only responding to music; it is also changing the way the music is heard. This could include muting and unmuting layers, changing volume, switching between parts, or controlling simple audio effects. The user may also interact with this mechanic through mouse or keyboard input, such as moving an object that changes the mix. This makes the piece feel more interactive and performative.

Possible controls include mouse position, object collision, visual zones, volume mapping, and mute or unmute states.

![Visual audio control sketch](images/visual-audio-control-sketch.png)

---

## Part 3: Putting It Together

The final piece will work as a connected audiovisual system. The WAV file will provide the main sound, while MIDI data will create accurate musical triggers. Random animation and background visuals will respond to these musical outputs, while some visual elements will also control the audio by changing volume, muting, or switching parts. FFT analysis of the final sound output will add another layer of response, allowing the visuals to react to the sound after it has been shaped by the artwork. This creates one coherent piece where music and visuals influence each other.

